      <hedline>
        <hl1>Becoming a Parent</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Rachel Fink letter on Zev Rosenwaks's June 24 article urges aging women unable to restore their fertility to consider adoption</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I agree wholeheartedly with ''We Still Can't Stop the Biological Clock,'' by Zev Rosenwaks (Op-Ed, June 24). As a veteran of five years of infertility treatments, and as a professor of embryology, I know how very real a biological clock can be.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I agree wholeheartedly with ''We Still Can't Stop the Biological Clock,'' by Zev Rosenwaks (Op-Ed, June 24). As a veteran of five years of infertility treatments, and as a professor of embryology, I know how very real a biological clock can be.</p>
        <p>I would like to add a hopeful note, however, for those trying to beat the odds: Once the dream of pregnancy can be let go, contact a professional adoption agency. Nothing has made me feel younger, or more alive, than my two adopted children. The fable of rewinding the biological clock may not come true, but the fountain of youth really does exist -- it is called parenthood by adoption.</p>
        <p>RACHEL FINK  South Hadley, Mass., June 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
